1 The data

In this tutorial we will be working with data from the World Happiness Report, a project that collects global survey data on how people evaluate their own lives in more than 150 countries worldwide. I downloaded the data from kaggle, and cleaned it to have common variables match. First download the clean data and place it in a data folder in your project.

We will use our usual read_csv() function, but instead of reading just one file, we will read files in our list of files to read.

library(tidyverse)
world_happiness <- read_csv("data/world_happiness.csv")

Not all variables are present for all years in the data, since these are yearly reports and the methods for data collection slightly change from year to year. You can get more information about the specifics of each year data collection from the World Happiness Report website.

2 Happiness and Healthy Life Expectancy

We will start by looking at the years 2021 and 2022, and the healthy_life_expectancy variable which is in years. We first filter the data for the specific years we want to explore.

world_happiness_2020_2021 <- world_happiness %>%
  filter(year == 2020 | year == 2021)

Our question relates to the relationship between happiness score and healthy life expectancy in years. Lets plot a scatterplot with these two numeric variables mapped to the axes. We will also add a regression line to the plot using geom_smooth().

world_happiness_2020_2021 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = healthy_life_expectancy,
             y = happiness_score)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Note that for our regression line in the plot above we used method = "lm" for a linear regression model. Lets run lm() with happiness_score as the dependent variable and healthy_life_expectancy as a predictor.

model_life_expc <- lm(happiness_score ~ healthy_life_expectancy,
                      data = world_happiness_2020_2021)

We now run summary() on the object we just created to get the coefficients and other information on the model.

summary(model_life_expc)

model_summary <- summary(model_life_expc)

model_summary$adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.5906958

3 Change in happiness scores over the years

Lets turn our attention to the entire data set. There are a total of 165 countries in the data, which is too much for visualizing all at once. Lets filter our data to look at some selected countries using %in%.

world_happiness %>%
  filter(country %in% c("United States", "Brazil", "Canada", "Mexico", "Bolivia",
                        "Switzerland", "Finland")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year,
             y = happiness_score,
             color = country)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~region)

It looks like theres an interaction between region and year.

4 Effect of categorical variable

We can run our linear regression with categorical predictors, like region.

model_region <- lm(happiness_score ~ region,
                   data = world_happiness)

The interpretation of results with a categorical variable with lots of levels using just summary() is really difficult. To get the effect of each level, I use the function effect() from the effects package.

library(effects)
region_effect <- effect("region", model_region) %>%
  data.frame() 


region_effect %>%
  kable()
region fit se lower upper

Sub-Saharan Africa 4.283713 0.0400685 4.205103 4.362324

We can plot these results, so they are easier to read. Remember that region is an unordered categorical variable, so we should reorder region by the fit (in this case the fit is the average happiness score).

region_effect %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = reorder(region, fit),
             x = fit,
             xmin = lower,
             xmax = upper)) +
  geom_errorbar() +
  geom_label(aes(label = format(fit, digits = 2)))

5 Multifactorial analysis

We can add predictors to our model with the + symbol.

model_multivariate <- lm(happiness_score ~ region + year,
                           data = world_happiness)

summary(model_multivariate)
